f VMI s small class size by giving oral exams in many of his psychology classes    15 minutes face to face on everything that has been covered in a semester   The map is not the terrain  Any examination offers only a limited snapshot of mastery  In the dialogue of an oral examination  I can get access to a map that more closely resembles the terrain of a student s understanding  And when it comes to the military aspect of the cadets  lives  Cotting knows what it s about  Having begun in his native Switzerland as an explosives expert in the sappers  a corps of elite combat engineers  he also served in the Swiss military as an adviser for refugee and prisoner affairs  By 2001  however  Cotting was settled in the United States  That was the year he became a U S  citizen and the year he earned his doctorate  It was also the year of the terrorist attacks on the World Trade Center and of his own decision to do something to help his adopted country in the aftermath  Cotting joined the U S  Army Medical Service Corps and  in 2004 as part of a Mental Health Advisory Team  traversed war torn Iraq assessing the psychological well being of U S  service members  Cotting traveled to 17 Forward Operations Bases in Iraq and Kuwait  which sometimes came under fire   One has to be a good follower before becoming a good leader  said Cotting   Here at VMI  you start at the bottom and you have a much better experience at interacting and leading individuals than you would get anywhere else  Lt  Col  Dave Cotting Associate Professor  Psychology Ph D  University of California Davis Specialty Leadership stress   coping  social personality psychology  and sports psychology     Share this entry Share on Facebook Share on Twitter Share on Google  Share on Linkedin Share on Tumblr Share on Reddit Share by Mail The Map is Not the Terrain January 18  2013 in Academic  Challenge  Faculty and Staff  by Kate When Lt  Col  Dave I  Cotting came to VMI in August 2007 as assistant professor of psycholog